            <!-- Pro Tips -->
            <section class="bg-slate-50 rounded-[2.5rem] p-8 border border-slate-100">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">Pro Tips to Avoid Common Delays</h2>
                <ul class="space-y-4 text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
                    <li><strong>Front-load your ECA and language tests.</strong> Both expire (ECA at 5 years, IELTS/CELPIP at 2 years). Schedule them before SIRS registration so they remain valid through nomination AND your federal PR application.</li>
                    <li><strong>Use a single, consistent name spelling</strong> across passport, work permits, ECA, employer letters, and IRCC forms. Mismatches trigger non-routine review.</li>
                    <li><strong>Get employer reference letters signed BEFORE you need them.</strong> Many applicants stall because a former HR manager has left the company. Letters must include job title, NOC code, duties, dates of employment, hours per week, and salary.</li>
                    <li><strong>Choose Express Entry BC whenever possible.</strong> The PR portion alone is 6 to 10 months faster than the base (non-EE) stream.</li>
                    <li><strong>Respond to BC PNP requests within 7 days.</strong> Most additional document requests give you 21 days, but fast turnaround keeps your file on the active reviewer's desk.</li>
                    <li><strong>Update your IRCC profile</strong> for any address, passport, or family composition changes within 30 days to avoid re-medical or re-biometric requests.</li>
