            <!-- Expanded FAQ -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-8">More Processing-Time Questions</h2>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Does the BC PNP processing clock pause when they request more documents?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. The published 2-3 month processing standard assumes a complete application. Each Request For Information (RFI) effectively pauses the clock until BC PNP receives and reviews your response. A single RFI can add 3-6 weeks.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>How long after nomination must I submit my federal PR application?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">For Express Entry BC, you must accept the provincial nomination in your IRCC EE profile and submit your e-APR within 60 days of receiving your Invitation to Apply (ITA). For the base (non-EE) stream, you have 6 months from the nomination certificate date.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Will the 2025 federal immigration levels cuts make processing slower in 2026?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">The 2025-2027 Immigration Levels Plan reduced PNP targets to 55,000 in 2025 and 55,000 in 2026. BC's nomination cap dropped to roughly 4,000 base allocations plus exemptions. Fewer nominations means more selectivity, not necessarily slower per-file processing. Tech and Health Authority remain the fastest-moving streams.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Does living in a Northeast or rural BC region speed up nomination?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes - regional Northeast Pilot draws and Northern Development Initiative bonuses can fast-track candidates with lower SIRS scores. The nomination review timeline is the same, but the wait for an invitation in the SIRS pool is often weeks rather than months.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>What happens if my biometrics or medical expire while waiting?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Biometrics are valid for 10 years, so they rarely expire. Medicals expire after 12 months. If your federal PR processing exceeds 12 months, IRCC will request a new medical and that adds 4-8 weeks to the timeline.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Is the "GCMS notes" request worth it to check delays?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes, if your file has been silent for more than the published processing standard. GCMS (or ATIP) notes cost $5 and take about 30 days to receive. They show exactly which security or background checks are pending, which medical office handled your file, and any officer notes - far more useful than the public tracker.</div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-blue-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
                        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Can I move out of BC after nomination but before PR?</span><span class="text-blue-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">▼</span></summary>
                        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">You must demonstrate the intent to live and work in BC at the time of nomination. Moving out of BC after nomination but before COPR can result in nomination revocation, which then causes IRCC to refuse your PR application. Stay in BC until you land as a PR.</div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </section>

